<section id="body">
	<p align="left">&#160;The bar chart shows the amount of time that <input id="1" type="droptarget" />-year-olds in England spend per week on sport and exercise. It is clear from the chart that <input id="2" type="droptarget" /> are less active in their leisure time than <input id="3" type="droptarget" />.</p><p align="left">There is a striking difference between the percentages of men and women who prefer not to participate in sport in their free time. Almost <font color="#0000ff"><input id="4" type="droptarget" /></font> of young women devote no time at all to active leisure pursuits while this applies to only about <font color="#0000ff"><input id="5" type="droptarget" /></font> of young men. There is a similar difference between the percentages of very active young people. Almost <font color="#0000ff"><input id="6" type="droptarget" /></font> men between the ages of 16 and 24 play sport for <font color="#0000ff"><input id="7" type="droptarget" /></font> or more hours a week. The figure for young women is only <font color="#0000ff"><input id="8" type="droptarget" /></font>.</p><p align="left">A closer examination of the figures for young people who actually play sport reveals that the greatest proportion dedicate between <font color="#0000ff"><input id="9" type="droptarget" /></font> hours per week to these pastimes. This is true for just over <font color="#0000ff"><input id="10" type="droptarget" /></font> of both men and women.</p><p align="left">The fact that only <font color="#0000ff"><input id="11" type="droptarget" /></font> of young women spend an hour or more a week on sport, compared to approximately <font color="#0000ff"><input id="12" type="droptarget" /></font> of young men, raises questions about how fit young women are in comparison to young men.</p><p align="left"><font size="2"></font></p><img class="leftFloat" src="../Media/LE_AW_1n4.jpg" height="" width="" mode="1" id="1003"  />
